Court held at Southampton before the aforesaid mayor and bailiffs, on the Tuesday before the Feast of St. Denys the Martyr, 8 Henry IV.1

Thomas Mannyng and Katerina his wife laid before the court a deed Whereby they granted to Sir Gilbert Harryye, chaplain, a tenement, with garden adjacent, situated in the parish of Holy Rood, on the east side of English Street, between a tenement of Thomas Wellys, formerly belonging to John Polymond, on the north and a tenement of John Curtenay on the south; and the said tenement is a hundred and forty-two standard feet in length from the eastvvard and fifteen and a half feet in breadth on the front and thirteen and three-quarters feet at the baclr; the said Gilbert and his heirs to hold the aforesaid tenement for ever of the chief lords of the fee by the customary services.

Clause of warranty.

Sealed by grantors and with mayor’s seal, “because our seals are unknown to many.”
